Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) is a design pattern that improves the reliability of large language models by combining retrieval and generation. Instead of relying only on the model’s internal memory, a RAG system first searches an external knowledge base for relevant documents. These retrieved chunks are then inserted into the prompt so the model can answer using grounded context. This reduces hallucination, improves factual accuracy, and makes the system easier to update because the knowledge can be changed by replacing documents rather than retraining the model.

A typical RAG pipeline has three main stages: ingestion, retrieval, and generation. During ingestion, source documents are collected, cleaned, chunked into smaller passages, converted into embeddings, and stored in a vector database. During retrieval, the user’s question is embedded and compared with stored vectors to find the most relevant chunks. During generation, those chunks are passed to the LLM along with the user question so the answer is based on the retrieved evidence.

Model Context Protocol, or MCP, is a standardized way for AI assistants to interact with external tools, APIs, and context providers. Instead of building one-off integrations for every tool, MCP provides a consistent interface that allows models to discover capabilities, request context, and call tools in a structured way. This improves interoperability between assistants and external systems and helps developers build reusable AI integrations.

AI Agents are software systems designed to pursue goals by reasoning over context, planning steps, and taking actions. Unlike a single prompt-response interaction, an agent can use memory, tools, and iterative decision-making to solve more complex tasks. Agents often break larger problems into sub-tasks, call external services, verify intermediate results, and adjust their behavior based on feedback. This makes them useful for workflows such as code generation, test orchestration, research assistance, and document analysis.

LLM evaluation is important because language models are probabilistic and non-deterministic. Traditional pass/fail testing is often not enough. In RAG systems, important quality metrics include faithfulness, answer relevance, context precision, and context recall. Faithfulness measures whether the answer is fully supported by the retrieved context. Answer relevance measures whether the response directly addresses the user’s question. Context precision checks how relevant the retrieved documents are, while context recall checks whether the retrieval step missed important supporting information.

Cypress can support AI-powered testing by combining browser automation with intelligent test assistance. AI can help identify brittle selectors, support self-healing when UI changes occur, and assist with natural-language-driven validation of workflows. In modern quality engineering, Cypress can also be part of larger AI-assisted pipelines where failures are analyzed, grouped, and prioritized automatically based on confidence and impact.